<paragraph id="016C1165FF883950EBD2C223FE8B5E1C" blockId="38.[227,372,1296,1322]" box="[227,372,1296,1322]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">
<heading id="5A24A609FF883950EBD2C223FE8B5E1C" bold="true" box="[227,372,1296,1322]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" reason="3">
<emphasis id="33A7CD77FF883950EBD2C223FE8B5E1C" bold="true" box="[227,372,1296,1322]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Description</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="016C1165FF883950EBD2C271FED05D85" blockId="38.[227,1439,1346,1715]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">
The species is characterized by massive, more or less elliptic otoliths that are high in the center, with a protruding dorsal rim. This protruding dorsal part of the otoliths is sharply raised, making its anterior rim and particularly the posterior one steep and angled. The anterior and the ventral rims are, overall, smoothly curved. The posterior rim of the otolith is extended and its shape varies; it is angled in the 
<typeStatus id="DE68AFC7FF883950EBD4C2E9FEB35EC2" box="[229,332,1498,1524]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">holotype</typeStatus>
(
<figureCitation id="99E80DE0FF883950EA6CC2E9FE3B5EC3" box="[349,452,1498,1525]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="36.[227,270,1824,1850]" captionTargetBox="[227,1437,672,1791]" captionTargetId="figure-189@36.[227,1437,672,1791]" captionTargetPageId="36" captionText="Fig. 11. Fish otoliths from the US middle and upper Eocene. A–D. Ariosoma nonsector Nolf &amp; Stringer, 2003. A–C. Wheelock M., Little Brazos River, Stenzel loc., Texas (IRSNB P 9993–9995).D. “Stone City beds”, Stone City Bluff, Brazos River, sample 5 from bed S, Texas (IRSNB P 9996). E–F. Paraconger wechesensis sp. nov., Weches F., Wall Farm 1, Texas. E. Holotype (IRSNB P 9997). F. Paratype (IRSNB P 9998). G–L. Paraconger brazosensis (Dante &amp; Frizzell, 1965), “Stone City beds”, Stone City Bluff, Brazos River, sample 2 from bed P, Texas (IRSNB P 9999–10004). 1 = ventral view; 2 = inner view. Scale bars = 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6484378" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6484378/files/figure.png" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Fig. 11E</figureCitation>
) but tapering upwards in many of the smaller specimens (
<figureCitation id="99E80DE0FF883950EF47C2E9FB215EC3" box="[1142,1246,1498,1525]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="36.[227,270,1824,1850]" captionTargetBox="[227,1437,672,1791]" captionTargetId="figure-189@36.[227,1437,672,1791]" captionTargetPageId="36" captionText="Fig. 11. Fish otoliths from the US middle and upper Eocene. A–D. Ariosoma nonsector Nolf &amp; Stringer, 2003. A–C. Wheelock M., Little Brazos River, Stenzel loc., Texas (IRSNB P 9993–9995).D. “Stone City beds”, Stone City Bluff, Brazos River, sample 5 from bed S, Texas (IRSNB P 9996). E–F. Paraconger wechesensis sp. nov., Weches F., Wall Farm 1, Texas. E. Holotype (IRSNB P 9997). F. Paratype (IRSNB P 9998). G–L. Paraconger brazosensis (Dante &amp; Frizzell, 1965), “Stone City beds”, Stone City Bluff, Brazos River, sample 2 from bed P, Texas (IRSNB P 9999–10004). 1 = ventral view; 2 = inner view. Scale bars = 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6484378" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6484378/files/figure.png" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Fig. 11F</figureCitation>
). The inner face is convex and the outer face is slightly concave but swollen in the center. The sulcus is wide, nearly straight and not distinctively divided into ostium and cauda; it opens very restrictedly to the anterodorsal rim of the otolith. A single large elevated colliculum fills the entire sulcus. A marked constriction in the posterior part of the crista inferior is followed by a broad ventrally extended posterior end of the cauda.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="49C942EEFF883950EBD2C1EDFEB75338" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="016C1165FF883950EBD2C1EDFEAA5DCE" blockId="38.[227,341,1758,1784]" box="[227,341,1758,1784]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">
<heading id="5A24A609FF883950EBD2C1EDFEAA5DCE" bold="true" box="[227,341,1758,1784]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" reason="3">
<emphasis id="33A7CD77FF883950EBD2C1EDFEAA5DCE" bold="true" box="[227,341,1758,1784]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Remarks</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="016C1165FF883950EBD2C03CFEB75338" blockId="38.[227,1438,1807,2062]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">
The otoliths of this species are readily distinguished from those of the co-occurring related species, 
<taxonomicName id="C6D36AE6FF883950EBD2C005FCCC5C66" authority="(Dante &amp; Frizzell, 1965)" baseAuthorityName="Dante &amp; Frizzell" baseAuthorityYear="1965" box="[227,819,1845,1872]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Congridae" genus="Paraconger" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anguilliformes" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="brazosensis">
<emphasis id="33A7CD77FF883950EBD2C005FDFE5C79" box="[227,513,1845,1871]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Paraconger brazosensis</emphasis>
(Dante &amp; 
<bibRefCitation id="65426C94FF883950E9B3C006FCD55C66" author="Frizzell D. L." box="[642,810,1845,1872]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" pagination="85 - 110" refId="ref53928" refString="Frizzell D. L. 1965. Otolith-based genera and lineages of fossil bonefishes (Clupeiformes, Albulidae). Senckenbergiana Lethaea 46 a: 85 - 110." type="book chapter" year="1965">Frizzell, 1965</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="C6D36AE6FF883950E873C005FBA05C79" authority="(Koken, 1888)" baseAuthorityName="Koken" baseAuthorityYear="1888" box="[834,1119,1845,1871]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Congridae" genus="Paraconger" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anguilliformes" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="sector">
<emphasis id="33A7CD77FF883950E873C005FC565C79" box="[834,937,1846,1871]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">P. sector</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="65426C94FF883950E889C006FBA95C79" author="Koken" box="[952,1110,1845,1871]" firstAuthor="Koken" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" pagination="274 - 305" refId="ref54599" refString="Koken E. 1888. Neue Untersuchungen an tertiaren Fisch-Otolithen. Zeitschrift der deutschen geologischen Gesellschaft 40: 274 - 305." type="journal article" year="1888">Koken, 1888</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="C6D36AE6FF883950EF93C005FE725C40" authority="Nolf &amp; Stringer, 2003" authorityName="Nolf &amp; Stringer" authorityYear="2003" class="Actinopterygii" family="Congridae" genus="Paraconger" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anguilliformes" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="yazooensis">
<emphasis id="33A7CD77FF883950EF93C005FAC05C79" box="[1186,1343,1846,1871]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">P. yazooensis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="65426C94FF883950EE76C006FE725C40" author="Nolf &amp; Stringer" firstAuthor="Nolf" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" pagination="1 - 23" refId="ref56290" refString="Nolf D. &amp; Stringer G. L. 2003. Late Eocene (Priabonian) fish otoliths from the Yazoo Clay at Copenhagen, Louisiana. Louisiana Geological Survey Geological Pamphlet 13: 1 - 23." type="journal article" year="2003">Nolf &amp; Stringer, 2003</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, by their more compact outline and wider and rounded ventral area. They have a slightly more extended posterior part than those of 
<taxonomicName id="C6D36AE6FF883950E9C0C0B1FC9A5CAA" authorityName="Muller" authorityYear="1999" box="[753,869,1922,1948]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Congridae" genus="Paraconger" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anguilliformes" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="solidus">
<emphasis id="33A7CD77FF883950E9C0C0B1FC9A5CAA" box="[753,869,1922,1948]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">P. solidus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="99E80DE0FF883950E849C0B1FC1B5CAA" box="[888,996,1922,1948]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="97.[227,270,1612,1638]" captionTargetId="figure-20@98.[227,1437,302,1907]" captionTargetPageId="98" captionText="Fig. 38 (opposite page). Fish otoliths from the US middle and upper Eocene. A. “Ophichthus” brevior (Koken, 1888), holotype (ZMB Ot. 26), “Jackson Beds”, Mississippi (?). B. Gnathophis dissimilis (Frizzell &amp; Lamber, 1962), Moodys Branch F., Town Creek, Jackson, Mississippi (IRSNB P 9038). C. Paraconger solidus Müller, 1999, holotype (coll. Institut für Geowissenschaften, University of Leipzig, Nr. 10/P67), Piney Point F., loc. 24 (Horseshoe) of Müller, 1999, Virginia. D–G. Paraconger yazooensis Nolf &amp; Stringer, 2003, Yazoo Clay, Tullos M., Copenhagen, Louisiana. D. Holotype (IRSNB P 6962). E–G. Paratypes (IRSNB P 6963–6965). H. Muraenanguilla aff. thevenini (Priem, 1906), Yazoo Clay, Copenhagen, Louisiana (IRSNB P 6966). I. Signata nicoli Dante &amp; Frizzell, 1965, Weches F., Pleasanto, Atascosa County, Texas, holotype (USNM 23370). J. Xenosirembo decipiens (Koken, 1888), lectotype (ZMB Ot. 135), middle Eocene, “Clayborne Group”, southern USA. K. Brotula aquitanica Nolf, 1980, Yazoo Clay, Tullos M., Copenhagen, Louisiana (IRSNB P 7419). L–O. Aequalobythites aequaloides (Nolf &amp; Stringer, 2003), Yazoo Clay, Copenhagen, Louisiana.L. Holotype (IRSNB P 6977). M–O. Paratypes (IRSNB P 6978–6980). 1 = ventral view; 2 = inner view. Scale bars = 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6491387" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6491387/files/figure.png" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Fig. 38C</figureCitation>
) from the Piney Point Formation of 
<collectingRegion id="C317DF87FF883950EBD2C09BFEB95CF4" box="[227,326,1960,1986]" country="United States of America" name="Virginia" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Virginia</collectingRegion>
. 
<taxonomicName id="C6D36AE6FF883950EA60C09AFD8C5CF4" authority="Lin &amp; Nolf &amp; Steurbaut, 2022" authorityName="Lin &amp; Nolf &amp; Steurbaut" authorityYear="2022" box="[337,627,1960,1986]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Congridae" genus="Paraconger" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anguilliformes" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="wechesensis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="33A7CD77FF883950EA60C09AFD8C5CF4" box="[337,627,1960,1986]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Paraconger wechesensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="2894700CFF883950E94BC09BFD2A5CF4" box="[634,725,1960,1986]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is currently confined to the Weches Formation; however, the available specimens are not always perfectly preserved; many of them are somewhat worn and surface abraded.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
